I"Œ<p>It‚Äôs hard to think of something more at the core of society than the family dwelling. It‚Äôs where you hang your hat, put your family possessions, and spend time with the ones you are closest to. For many families in Ulaanbaatar, this means an apartment in a multi-level building.</p>

<p>As children grow up, get married, and have children (but not always in that order), families often scrape together enough money to purchase an apartment for the budding young family to start their lives together. It sounds quite idylic, something akin to a ‚ÄúMongolian Dream‚Äù rivaling the American one.</p>

<p>It‚Äôs easy to argue that this Mongolian Dream is a false one, propped up by a highly profitable construction sector, but that‚Äôs not what I‚Äôm here to do. I‚Äôm here to answer a Tweet. That‚Äôs right, a Tweet. Perhaps you get motivated by lofty ideals or a sense of justice. I tend to pay attention to Twitter too much.</p>

